{
  "answer": "Several works in the corpus discuss rules for offering hospitality to a guest (atithi). The most detailed treatment is in the Manusmṛti (unknown-manusmrti-347b76), chapters 3 and 4, which prescribes: honoring guests is the 'sacrifice to men' (one of the five great daily sacrifices); a householder must give an arriving atithi a seat and water; guests should be fed before the householder eats; a guest who arrives at sunset must not be turned away; and failing to honor guests brings sin. The Parāśara Smṛti (unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be), chapter 1, similarly mandates hospitality to the atithi alongside the Vaiśvadeva rite, and warns that those who exclude the atithi from hospitality go to hell. The Yājñavalkya Smṛti (unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6), chapter 1, lists 'hospitality to guests' as one of the mahāyajñas (great sacrifices) incumbent on the householder. The Āṅgirasa Smṛti (unknown-angirasa-smtp-2bf9d1), chapter 1, also mentions the worship of the guest (atithi) as a ritual duty and instructs that food should be accepted and given to one's guru, fire, and guests. Outside the Sanskrit Smritis, Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana (unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a, chapter 1) portrays a virtuous couple whose 'faith in guests was great,' illustrating hospitality as a dharmic virtue in the Kawi tradition.",
